ctionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>brigge</i> ‘bridge’, Old English <i>brycg</i>, applied as a topographic name for someone who lived near a bridge, a metonymic occupational name for a bridge keeper, or a habitational name from any of the places called with this element, as for example Bridge in Kent or Bridge Sollers in Herefordshire. Building and maintaining bridges was one of the three main feudal obligations, along with bearing arms and maintaining fortifications. The cost of building a bridge was often defrayed by charging a toll, the surname thus being acquired by the toll gatherer."],"variants":[{"name":"Bridges","meanings":["English: variant of   Bridge  . The <i>-s</i> generally represents the genitive case, but may occasionally be a plural. In some cases this name denoted someone from the Flemish city of Bruges (Brugge) in Belgium, meaning ‘bridges’, which had extensive trading links with England in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Bridger","meanings":["English: from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>brigge</i>, <i>brugge</i> ‘bridge’ (Old English <i>brycg</i>), denoting either someone who lived near a bridge or the keeper of a bridge. See   Bridge  .","Americanized form of German <b>Brücker</b> (see   Brucker  )."]},{"name":"Burge","meanings":["English: variant of   Bridge  , Old English <i>brycg</i>, with metathesis of <i>u</i> and <i>r</i>, as exemplified in several placenames of this origin in various parts of southern England.","Swiss German and German (<b>Bürge</b>): from Middle High German <i>bürge</i> ‘bailsman, guarantor’. Compare   Buerge  ."]},{"name":"Bridgeman","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>brigge</i>, <i>brugge</i> ‘bridge’ (Old English <i>brycg</i>) + <i>man</i>, denoting either a dweller by or a keeper of a bridge. See   Bridge  .","In some cases possibly also an Americanized form (translation into English) of German <b>Bruckmann</b> (see   Bruckman  ).","History: James Bridgeman or Bridgman (1620–76) came to Hartford, CT, from Winchester, Hampshire, England, in 1640."]},{"name":"Brugman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Erna, Kurt.","Dutch: topographic name for someone who lived near a bridge or a metonymic occupational name for a bridge keeper, from Dutch <i>brug</i> ‘bridge’ (see   Bridge  ). Compare   Bruggeman  .","Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Bruggmann</b> ‘bridge keeper’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Bridge was born about 1560 as the son of Bridge. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1560–":"umbes 1560–Surnud","1560–Male":"1560–Surnud","1580–Male":"1580–Surnud","1540–Male":"1540–Surnud","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","about 1560":"umbes 1560"},"fi":{"about 1560–":"noin 1560–Kuollut","1560–Male":"1560–Kuollut","1580–Male":"1580–Kuollut","1540–Male":"1540–Kuollut","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","about 1560":"noin 1560"},"fr":{"about 1560–":"environ 1560–Décédé","1560–Male":"1560–Décédé","1580–Male":"1580–Décédé","1540–Male":"1540–Décédé","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","about 1560":"environ 1560","lifeSummary":"Bridge est né environ 1560, fils de Bridge. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"about 1560–":"um 1560–Verstorben","1560–Male":"1560–Verstorben","1580–Male":"1580–Verstorben","1540–Male":"1540–Verstorben","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","about 1560":"um 1560","lifeSummary":"Bridge wurde um 1560, als Sohn von Bridge geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1560–":"about 1560–Desede","1560–Male":"1560–Desede","1580–Male":"1580–Desede","1540–Male":"1540–Desede","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","about 1560":"about 1560"},"hu":{"about 1560–":"1560 körül–elhunyt","1560–Male":"1560–elhunyt","1580–Male":"1580–elhunyt","1540–Male":"1540–elhunyt","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","about 1560":"1560 körül"},"id":{"about 1560–":"sekitar 1560–Telah Meninggal","1560–Male":"1560–TelahMeni